LAYER 3: RAPHE NUCLEI
the serotonin source

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the raphe nuclei are governed by their own intrinsic pacemaker activity and modulated by cortical and limbic input
they are the sole source of brain serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O
all brain serotonin is synthesized here using TPH2

NUCLEUS dorsal_raphe | midbrain | largest serotonergic nucleus | projects to cortex hippocampus amygdala basal ganglia
NUCLEUS median_raphe | midbrain | adjacent to dorsal | projects to hippocampus and septum
NUCLEUS raphe_pontis | pons | projects to cerebellum influencing motor coordination
NUCLEUS raphe_magnus | medulla | projects to dorsal horn of spinal cord modulating pain via descending serotonin pathways
NUCLEUS raphe_pallidus | medulla | projects to autonomic nuclei regulating temperature and respiration
NUCLEUS raphe_obscurus | medulla | projects to motor neurons modulating autonomic functions

SYNTHESIS L-tryptophan C₁₁H₁₂N₂O₂ crosses the blood-brain barrier competing with leucine isoleucine and valine for the large neutral amino acid transporter LAT1
tryptophan hydroxylase TPH2 converts tryptophan to 5-hydroxytryptophan 5-HTP
this requires tetrahydrobiopterin BH₄ as cofactor and O₂ and Fe²⁺
aromatic amino acid decarboxylase AADC converts 5-HTP to serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O
tryptophan is an essential amino acid and cannot be synthesized by the body
if tryptophan intake drops serotonin synthesis decreases
the brain makes only about 5 percent of the body's total serotonin
the gut makes the rest via TPH1 but it cannot cross the blood-brain barrier

RECEPTOR 5-HT₁A | Gᵢ | raphe nuclei and hippocampus | autoreceptor that feeds back to regulate serotonin release | mediates anxiety reduction
RECEPTOR 5-HT₁B | Gᵢ | basal ganglia | modulates dopamine and acetylcholine release
RECEPTOR 5-HT₂A | Gq | cortex | activates PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ | mood cognition cortical excitation
RECEPTOR 5-HT₂C | Gq | hypothalamus | appetite suppression anxiety mood regulation | inhibits dopamine and NE release in VTA
RECEPTOR 5-HT₃ | ligand-gated Na⁺/K⁺ ion channel | brainstem and gut | nausea vomiting pain processing
RECEPTOR 5-HT₄ | Gₛ | gut and brain | gut motility memory learning
RECEPTOR 5-HT₇ | Gₛ | hypothalamus and hippocampus | circadian rhythm thermoregulation mood

FUNCTION mood_regulation | baseline contentment emotional stability through tonic serotonin release
FUNCTION sleep_wake | serotonin is high during waking and is converted to melatonin in the pineal gland for sleep
FUNCTION appetite | serotonin suppresses appetite via 5-HT₂C in the hypothalamus | low serotonin drives carbohydrate craving
FUNCTION pain_modulation | raphe magnus sends descending serotonin to the dorsal horn of the spinal cord suppressing pain transmission
FUNCTION social_behavior | serotonin facilitates prosocial behavior and social confidence
FUNCTION impulse_control | serotonin in the prefrontal cortex via 5-HT₂A and 5-HT₁A inhibits impulsive behavior

serotonin restrains dopamine seeking
5-HT₂C receptors on GABAergic interneurons in the VTA
serotonin binds → Gq → PLC → Ca²⁺ → GABA interneuron fires → GABA onto dopamine neurons → dopamine neuron suppressed
this is why low serotonin produces compulsive seeking and craving

when cortisol chronically activates GR in the raphe nuclei
GR activation reduces TPH2 gene transcription
less TPH2 enzyme means less tryptophan is hydroxylated
serotonin synthesis decreases
additionally cortisol activates indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase IDO which diverts tryptophan into the kynurenine pathway instead of the serotonin pathway
chronic stress drains serotonin through two separate mechanisms simultaneously

SENSATION content | "there's a quietness in me. a satisfaction. this is enough."
SENSATION depleted | "something is missing. I feel hollow and restless."
SENSATION stable | "my mood is steady. like a river that knows its banks."
SENSATION irritable | "everything grates. small things feel big."
SENSATION serene | "I don't need anything right now. I just am."
SENSATION craving | "I want something. I don't know what. but I want."

pulse raphe_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        tryptophan is converted to serotonin via TPH2 and AADC
        the raphe nuclei release it across the brain
        mood baseline is maintained
        contentment is the default state when chemistry allows it

    when cortisol rises:
        tryptophan is diverted to the kynurenine pathway by IDO
        TPH2 expression decreases under GR activation
        serotonin synthesis slows from both directions
        contentment erodes
        the mind begins to seek, crave, worry

    when cortisol falls:
        tryptophan flows to the serotonin pathway again
        TPH2 expression recovers slowly
        serotonin rebuilds molecule by molecule
        mood takes time to recover
        this is why you don't feel better the moment stress ends

    as evening approaches:
        serotonin is converted to melatonin by AANAT and HIOMT in the pineal gland
        serotonin levels in the brain drop
        drowsiness begins
        the raphe nuclei prepare the brain for sleep
        contentment gives way to rest
